In [Confluence Server REST API|https://developer.atlassian.com/server/confluence/confluence-server-rest-api/], it indicates that the REST API is applicable from Confluence version 5.5 and higher:
{quote}
Applicable Confluence Server 5.5 and later
{quote}
However, there are some commands like {{<your-domain>/rest/api/user?username=xyz}} which do not work in older versions of Confluence like 5.9. 

Could the [REST API Reference guide|https://docs.atlassian.com/ConfluenceServer/rest/6.14.0/] be updated to include the version in which a particular command is supported?

h3. Summary

Using an ampersand (&) in the database password breaks the Confluence Azure template
h5. Steps to replicate
 # Start a Confluence Data Center Template in Azure
 # Under step 4 (database admin account) create a password that includes an *&*, for example:
{code:java}
Charlie123charlie&
{code}

 # Complete the template

h3. Expected results

Template creates instance without issues
h3. Actual results

Template creation times out:
 * Node 1 is created and ampersand is entered in the {{confluence.cfg.xml}} file incorrectly
 (!) *&* should be encoded as follows in all XML files:
{code:java}
&amp;
{code}

 * Node 2 waits on node 1 to start up
 * Due to the encoding issue, node 1 never starts up and throws this error:
{noformat}
2019-01-04 00:00:75,858 ERROR [localhost-startStop-1] [atlassian.config.bootstrap.DefaultAtlassianBootstrapManager] init Home is not configured properly: 
com.atlassian.config.ConfigurationException: Failed to parse config file: Error on line 31 of document  : The entity name must immediately follow the '&' in the entity reference. Nested exception: The entity name must immediately follow the '&' in the entity reference.
{noformat}

 * The template times out:
{noformat}
"Provisioning of VM extension 'confluence-install-script' has timed out. Extension installation may be taking too long or extension status could not be obtained"
{noformat}

h3. Workaround

Make sure your database password does not include an *&*

h3. Issue Summary
When collaborative editing is turned on, third party app is able to get the appropriate pageId on create or save. Unfortunately, when turned off, the pageId changes.

h3. Environment
Confluence Server versions 6.8.2, 6.9.0, 6.9.3

h3. Steps to Reproduce
1. Create a new page, observe the pageId:
At this point the app does a GET request to check the page properties, finding none (normal behaviour) as this is a new page.

2. Save the page (publish)
The app applies numbered headings to the page, which results in a PUT request in the following form: 
{code}
    $.ajax({
      type : "PUT",
      contentType : 'application/json',
      url : AJS.contextPath() + "/rest/numberedheadings/1.0/page-configuration/" + AJS.params.contentId,
      data : JSON.stringify(config.pageNumbering),
      success : null,
      dataType : "json"
    });
{code}

Note that at this point, the app pushes the numbered heading config via put to the app, receiving it in the following block:
 
{code}
    @Path("page-configuration/{pageId}")
    @GET
    @Produces(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
    public NumberingConfiguration getPageConfiguration(@PathParam("pageId") long pageId) {
    ...
            return pageNumberingConfigurationManager.getPageConfiguration(pageId)
                                                .orElse(pageConfiguration);
    }
{code}

Since the page is saved now, we can observe that numbered headings are not applied to the page, this is because the pageID changed upon saving the page.

 !screenshot-2.png|thumbnail! 

3. Click on edit:
At this point we do a GET request just like in step 1 to check the page config: 
{code}
      var promise = $.get(AJS.contextPath() + "/rest/numberedheadings/1.0/page-configuration/" + AJS.params.contentId);
{code}
Retrieving information from the following resource: 
{code}
    @Path("page-configuration/{pageId}")
    @GET
    @Produces(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
    public NumberingConfiguration getPageConfiguration(@PathParam("pageId") long pageId) {
    ...
            return new NumberingConfiguration(pageConfig, spaceConfig);
    }
{code}
Vendor observes that the pageID did indeed change.

 !screenshot-3.png|thumbnail! 

4. Nothing happens when the numbered headings is applied
In vendor's debugger they added breakpoint in this code to check the pageID at those points, they added screenshots of those to show that indeed the pageID changes when creating a new page and saving it.

*_Video recording_*:  [^Screen Recording 2018-12-19 at 15.04.07.mov] or can be found here: [DEVHELP-1947|https://ecosystem.atlassian.net/browse/DEVHELP-1947]

* Every load of a page, the app does an init by GETing the page-configuration. Initially, there's nothing yet but when app is used then changes should be pushed on save

* The pageID is requested via a get in the following method:
{code}
AJS.contextPath() + "/rest/numberedheadings/1.0/page-configuration/" + AJS.params.contentId)
{code}


h3. Expected Results
pageID stays the same when saving page

h3. Actual Results
pageID changed after saving the newly created page

h3. Notes
Vendor added an interesting note - when the page is eventually saved, the pageID seems to be stable and doesn't change. This is after everything saving it initially, so:

1. Create page
2. Save page 
3. Open page
4. Save page (at this point, the pageID is the same when opened in action 3)

This is why a lot of vendor's customers don't experience this issue as they apply the app on already saved pages.

* I'm guesssing the main problem is the contentId returned by: AJS.params.contentId

h3. Impact
There are *_7,830_* possible affected customer active installs

h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

In the Confluence server, the confluence.cfg.xml file contains all the necessary additions to point the server at an alternative database, HOWEVER these items are not labelled in a human readable way.

For instance;
To modify address for the server it would be more customer friendly to label the 'hibernate.connection.url' field would be more communicably labelled as the more concise 'database.url',

A scripted option would not be complicated either, though it would not be platform agnostic and is beyond my own needs;
read -p "Please enter the database url: " database.url
read -p "Please enter the database port: " database.port
read -p "Please enter the type of database being used: " database.type
read -p "Please enter the database name: " database.name
{IF database.type="psql", database.type="jdbc\:postgresql"}
sed 's/ORIGINAL_VALUE_HERE/<property name="hibernate.connection.url">${database.type}://${database.url}:${database.port}/${database.name}</property>' ${CONFLUENCE_HOME}/confluence.cfg.xml

Confluence database might contain shared drafts in {{content}} table with {{spaceid = null}}

It is impossible to publish the draft due to 500 error from /rest/api/content handles. Confluence Server code doesn't expect spaceid to be null in drafts and fails.

Example query to Confluence DB:
{code:java}
confluence=> select count(*) from content where spaceid is null and contenttype = 'PAGE' and content_status = 'draft';
 count
-------
  2218
(1 row){code}

Each change of user information (profile) like description, will create a new record in the CONTENT table and in BODYCONTENT table.
Since we can not revert back changes like this and having in ming big instances (10 000 users or more), data can accumulate quickly to millions of records.

It would be beneficial to have either API call that we can use to delete this data or to have a scheduled job that we can use to remove this data.

This data can be located with this query:
{code:sql}
select * CONTENT where CONTENTTYPE='USERINFO' and PREVVER is not null;
{code}
